description.text:
Objectives
  • Design a useful thing for your classroom.
  • Create something only by using round objects (and one prism).
  • Become familiar with round objects and simple extrusions in your CAD software.
    • Audiences
  • Everyone who wants to create an object that is done fast and looks well.
  • Especially students, who find use for it by using it in their classroom.
    • Preparation
  • Students have to use a computer and a CAD software of their choice.
  • Computer mice are helpful when working with CAD programs.
  • They should have worked a little bit with such programs but with a helpful teacher the project is also possible to finish if they haven´t got any expreience with CAD modelling.
  • The teacher shold not let them work completely on their own, because things like the extrusion may be a bit tricky without previous knowledge.
  • Working alone is possible but i recommend working in small groups to share ideas and suggested solutions.
  • Last but not least you need, of course, a 3D printer.
    • Steps
  • Collect ideas what objects could be useful in your classroom.
  • Decide on one thing and discuss how it should look like.
  • Check, whether your CAD software is able to work with all objects you want to use (prisms, pyramids, cylinders,...)
  • Start modelling the thing you agreed on.
  • Ask your teacher if you have problems with something.
  • Print the best looking models (maybe you can surprise other classes by giving them the chalk holder, or whatever, as a little present).
    • Results
  • At the end, you should have a useful thing for your classroom (here it is a chalk holder).
  • Students should be able to work with simple round objects without problems.
  • 10 chalks (5 - 6 white ones and 4 - 5 colored ones) are usually enough for one week. Choose one student each week who has to fill the holder up on monday morning and you will never again have the problem of not having a chalk in your classroom. :D

Modified Spool Platform Mount for above the printer - Prusa as is, but could be tranformed to others. Original GP Hook on which it is based generated some holes and a double face somewhere, but I finally found and fixed the holes, so they aren't a problem now. I mounted mine on the upper part of the printer on the same side as the electronics. I whittled the size of the platform clip down so that it could fit between the z-axis motor mount and the main structural frame. I have also created a filament guide to be mounted on the other side of the main frame. It is also posted on Thingiverse here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:122954

This allows for a horizontal mount of the filament, but keep several things in mind.
  • This mount can use a few vitamins for final construction, and I use the following:
    a. 1 toggle bolt with 2 nuts like in the picture posted above - my bolt is 4 inches and the nuts are 3/16.
    b. 1 matching hex nut, also pictured above to keep the top toggle nut from unwinding - same size as bolt.
    c. 1 printed spacer or insert to match your filament spool
    d. 1 vinyl or plastic cover cut to match filament spool
    • 2.What are these for?
    a. The toggle bolt & nuts keep the spool steady as it's pulled by the extruder with minimal friction
    b. The hex nut will keep the toggle bolt from unscrewing itself as long as two other conditions are also true:
    i. The hex nut is used as shown in the photo on top of the toggle nut
    ii. The filament turns the spool counter-clockwise as it is pulled
    c. With the toggle bolt & nuts with is less useful, but also acts to reduce spool wobble
    d. Sometimes a filament turned horizontal and not taut will begin to unwind from the spool. Ideally this would not happen and it certainly can cause overlap issues, but the sheet of plastic or vinyl will keep it from unwinding further and further minizes friction between the mount and the spool. I have learned from experience never to unwrap a filament spool until I'm ready to load it right into the extruder. One final comment about extrusion in general. There are several factors that affected my extrusion: A. I had lots of extrusion problems when I first built my MG PM. The first related to the problem solved by this spool mount. I started with using a mount on a bar that seemed like it would turn well, but would get bound up on long prints.
    B. The second problem related to not the tension of the bolts and springs on the extruder itself. I tried all kinds of temperature and speed changes to no avail. Finally I realized that I really just needed to tighten the bolts more, and the PLA behaved a lot better.
    C. Lastly, although I really like the MG extruder and the minimalistic simplicity of the mount for it, I made a bunch of other changes to increase the build height, so I needed a new extruder mount. This meant learning to print with ABS and slightly modifying a design I found on Thingiverse and posted here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:122560 Without Openscad and this extruder design I would have been screwed. I also used a spacer/washer design from Thingiverse, and generalized it into a module that can also use the cone property of the cylinder here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1224093

title: Equal Volume Solids Set + MakerEd Project

description.text:
This equal volume solids set is used to explain why bubbles are round. Spherical, to be exact. The sphere is the shape that uses the smallest surface area to enclose the largest volume! The set includes five solids: sphere, cube, pyramid, cylinder, and torus. Each has a volume of 125 cm3, and the surface areas range from 121 cm2 (sphere) to 168 cm2 (pyramid).
There are two Projects recommended with this set. One is to challenge students to make a bubble in another shape, using a frame or other method. Another is to challenge students to design another shape with the same volume as the set, using their knowledge of geometry and the 3D design program of their choice, and then to find its surface area.

Notes: These are uncomplicated models to print. Each is situated to provide the best resolution on the letters. Rafts are optional. Supports may interfere with the letters.

Calculations I used readily available geometry formulas to find the dimensions of various solid shapes with volume of 125cm3. Then I used those dimensions to find the surface area of each solid. Design Shapes were designed using Tinkercad. I created blocks of lettering that were angled or curved to match the surfaces of the shapes.

Objective Create a soap bubble with a shape other than a sphere (or near-sphere). Audience Kids or adults age 5 and up. Preparation
  • Print the Equal Volume Solids Set.
  • Prepare or purchase bubble solution. (I like the Guar Gum recipe at http://soapbubble.wikia.com/wiki/Recipes_Guar#Recipes , but any will work.)
  • Find or make some ordinary bubble wands. Clothesline wire or coat hangers work well.
  • Make some wands in different shapes (square, triangle).
  • Add some materials - string, straws, pipe cleaners, more wire, for making custom wands and frames.
    • Steps
  • Blow bubbles with a round wand. The bubbles are round(ish).
  • Blow bubbles with different shaped wands. Are the bubbles different shapes? Probably not.
  • Examine the Equal Volume Solids Set. Note that the sphere encloses the volume with the smallest possible surface area. Explain that bubbles are round for this reason. The bubble film has to stretch the least and can enclose a large volume of air.
  • Challenge students to make a bubble in a different shape. Frames that hold the bubble in place are allowed.
    • Results Invite students to share their bubble frames or wands, and demonstrate how they work.

description.header: Project Idea Two - Design a Solid
description.text:
Objective Practice precise 3D Design and geometry skills by creating a solid shape with a specific volume, and calculating its surface area. Audience Beginning 3D designers approximately age 13 and up, especially geometry students. Preparation
  • Print the Equal Volume Solids Set.
  • Find a reference list of formulas for volume and surface area of solids.
  • Introduce students to basics of 3D design, if this is completely new to them, using whatever program you want them to practice.
    • Steps
  • Show the Equal Volume Solids Set, and let students deduce the patterns of volume and surface area for the different shapes.
  • Challenge students to design a shape that has the same volume (125cm3), but is not one of the shapes in the set.
  • For advanced students, suggest grouping two or more shapes together to achieve the target volume.
  • Print or view student designs.
    • Results Let students share their work. Volume could be tested using displacement of water, if an objective assessment is desired.

This project was created to test the light transition and diffusion qualities of a printing material.
There are several different materials and colors available and all have different light properties when it comes to light. Since I am mainly using 3D prints to create tools for light painting photography i need a good method to check these properties. It also presents a nice project to learn something about 3D printing settings like fill patterns and layer management, so I created a learning challenge from this.

These boxes are created to find a good equilibrium between diffusion and transmission of light in a 3D printing material. It contains several box shaped models with a fitting for a regular 5mm LED. The inside of these boxes are designet to learn something about the properties of the material used to print the boxes.
Preview Text Markdown Enabled

Project: Light transmission and diffusion test With a few prints this project aims to find out the perfect shape and settings for a square shaped box lit by a 5mm LED. Objectives By printing different models and adjusting the settings for the print we can learn something about the properties of the used material when it comes to light. To have something to aim for this project aims to find a perfect model to use for a cool Larson scanner (think Battelstar Galactica or KnightRider)! Audiences For the material analysis part:
  • basic knowledge about 3D printing and where to find settings
  • beginner knowledge about electronics
    • For the Larson scanner part:
  • beginner soldering skills
  • beginner knowledge programming an Arduino
    • Preparation Find a partly transparent printing material. White materials work best, because you can use different colored LEDs with these. I used white PETG for this, which has pretty nice light transmission properties. Slightly transparent PETG is often sold as "pearl white".
    Full transparent materials are not very usable since this project also aims at researching the diffusion properties of the material, and with fully transparent materials this is mostly dependent on the fill pattern and not on the material. For the electronic part you will need some 5mm LEDs, a power source (batteries) and the proper resistors to light the LED with the voltage provided by your power source.
    Check the forward voltage and power consumption of you LEDs. By subtracting the forward voltage from the power supply voltage and using the power consumption of the LED you get the values to calculate the resistance needed for the resistor using ohms law.
    Keep in mind that the openings for the LEDs are designed to have a very tight fit, so you might not get them out without damaging the LED or box, so it is best to have a few extra. For the Larson scanner part you will need an Arduino (a Nano is enough and very cheap to get), a potentiometer (regular 10K ohm is great) for the speed control and some cables to put it all together. Steps! First we are looking for a good design and settings to get a perfect lit up square.
    Use standard settings for layers and infill for the initial test.
  • Start by printing a 20mm block without diffuser and no cone. Put a LED in and light it up. Check the side opposite of the LED and take a look on how the material is lit. If it shows a bright spot in the middle (pink example) you either need a cone to dimm the light in this area or a larger diffuser part. If the corners of the square are not lit up you will need a larger diffuser area.
  • Depending on the results of the first box print out another with larger diffuser area or a cone inside the box. Check the result again to see if the chosen way does give better results.
  • If you get a dark spot in the middle (blue example) then the cone is too big or not needed at all.
  • Once you found an even distribution of light take a closer look at the layer and infill settings. Usually slicing software use 3 layers at bottom, top and walls, so you will have at least 6 layers of 100% material. The pattern of these layers have a large influence on the light that shines through it. Also the pattern and percentage of the infill (if there is one because of layer height and/or diffuser size) have an impact on the light. Patterns like rectilinear, concentric or honeycomb work great in distributing the light evenly. (orange example shows a diffuser with concentric infill pattern cut open) Print the model you found with the other tests with these patterns to find the best. If you get one that is brighter then before you can probably reduce the diffuser size a bit (if you have any) because this pattern can transmit light very good.
  • If needed the SolidWorks models are included, so you can fine tune the cone shape and diffuser size.
  • Optional: if you want you can now try out a model with 30mm size and check the result with this. If the square is not lit up evenly try to apply the knowledge you gained from previous steps to get a better result. Using a 30mm box you can also aim for a box that has a dark frame but evenly lit inside (green example) for a nice and cool effect for the Larson scanner!
    • At this point you should have either a model that has an evenly lit side or one that has a dark frame but evenly lit inside. With this we will now build a cool Larson scanner with adjustable speed powered by an Arduino!
  • Print out 9 more boxes of you optimal model.
  • Use the Arduino and wire the parts according to the wiring diagram. Usually you should not power LEDs directly from the pins of the Arduino, but in this project there is only one lit most of the time (two for only 0.1 sec), so the Arduino should be fine. Also note that all LEDs share a common resistor on their negative side, again because only one (or two very briefly) are lit at any given time, so this saves some material.
  • Upload the provided sketch to the Arduino
  • Enjoy your very own self build Larson scanner!
    • Results In addition to the Larson scanner (if you build it) this project should have helped to understand how material, model design and printer/slicer settings influence how light shines through a 3D printed object. I used this to find good material width values and shapes to create my own light art performance photography tools. As an example lithographie uses this to create images that are only visible if an object is lit up (check out other cool projects by searching for this term!).

This is a model for a z axis topper for the Prusa I3 Steel (v4) XL edition.
This frame has a very reduced top part for the z axis and the threaded rod is spinning free, so I created this to fix the threaded rod in place.
It is designed to be clipped to the existing steel part and fastened with the existing screws (maybe need longer ones). Depending on material turn on supports to get the holes nice and clean. There is not much bridging, but depending on slicing software it might be a problem.

There is a fitting for a  MF126 ZZ bearing that is used to hold the threaded rod. Use a self locking nut to give a little tension on the threaded rod, so the nut is pressed against the bearing. This should take the tension of the couplers at the steppers and make the z axis much more smooth running.
Created using the original AutoCAD drawings of the steel laser cuttings.

Edit #2015-12-31# When I tried to add this to my printer i found a little design flaw. The clamps on the outer edge crashed into the vertical frame, so I reduced the length a bit.
Also added a little gap to the clamps, because the fit was too tight. If you downloaded the previous ones, please get the new ones, cause the previous ones won't fit on the frame!

description.text:
Update 8/10
  • Added bracket for GT2 belts - Recommend printing that bracket at .2 layer height
    • I had a few design goals for this part.
  • Use parts available at Home Depot
  • Be "tool less"
  • Be non destructive to the fascia
  • No more damn toothpicks
    • The tensioner consists of a top belt catch, 2 14mm adjuster knobs, and a bottom captive plate/foot. You need:
    4 x M4x30mm Hex Bolts (Home Depot small parts section)
    4 x M4 nuts Some notes on assembly:
    1) The skp files are dimensionally accurate +~.25mm. You can change them to suit your part or just print with 3-5% extra scaling. I printed my parts at 1.03 and 1.04 scaling and they came out "just right".
    2) the channels for the M4 bolts in the top plate should be have very little play but the bolts should be able to slide through them effortlessly. If they're too tight - just ream them out with a drill bit.
    3) the captive nuts should face the tensioner bottom/foot
    4) The foot keeps the parts secure and protects the wood from marring
    5) The bottom foot has a cavity cut out so it can sit on top of the cap screw :) I found that after about 50 hours on my printer, it needed a belt adjustment - the knobs make this effortless now :) Enjoy!

title: Z Lock M8 Threaded for MPCNC IE

description.text: I designed this Z Lock M8 full threaded for MPCNC IE because with the stock IE_z_nut_lock_13 mm always occurred the downward movement of the 13 mm nut even if I strong tightened the fixing screws but when using the CNC the nut will never remained in the clamping position with the consequent upward vertical loosening of the Z tower. For better and smooth running of the 8 mm Z rod inside this full threaded Z lock I recommend to heat approximately 70/80 degrees Celsius a screw M8X40 compatible with the thread of the rod Z to screw and unscrew it several times into the thread of Z Lock just printed and still warm, in this way the internal thread of the Z Lock will fit better the Z threaded rod of the central MPCNC tower to solve the listed issues. After mounting you can put on the thread of the Z rod  a few drops of oil which will help a more easy sliding.
